Note:
LaTeX Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the LaTeX translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    LaTeX source
      -> latex_lexer   (tokenize: commands, braces, math delimiters, text)
      -> latex_parser  (build LaTeX preamble/body AST)
      -> latex_to_hir  (lower AST to the self-contained kind-tagged HIR tree,
                        each node tagged with a HIR_LATEX_* constant at offset 0)
      -> hir_to_latex  (emit HIR back to LaTeX source text)

The orchestration entry points live in backends/latex/latex_emitter.runa:
latex_to_hir(source) drives lexer+parser+translator and returns the HIR
module; hir_to_latex(module) drives the backend and returns LaTeX text.

The probe feeds a representative document containing a \documentclass, a
\usepackage, a \section with a title, a \textbf formatting command, an
itemize environment with two \item entries, and an inline-math span. It then:

  1. Translates the source to HIR and asserts the HIR root is the LaTeX
     document module (type tag HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENT). The translator's
     add_to_module flattens every translated node into the module's items
     list (offset 16), so the probe walks that flat list and asserts the
     presence and structured attributes of each expected node kind:
     documentclass class name, usepackage package name, section title,
     bold-text payload, the itemize environment, two list items, and the
     inline-math node. LaTeX -> HIR is the lossless direction (every
     structural attribute is preserved as a typed field on the node), so
     these are exact structural asserts.

  2. Emits the HIR back to LaTeX text and asserts the text is non-empty and
     carries the \documentclass and \section sigils.

  3. Re-parses the emitted LaTeX back into HIR and asserts the re-parsed
     module preserves the document type, the documentclass class name, the
     section title, and the itemize environment - i.e. STRUCTURAL survival
     on the SECOND emission, not just non-empty output.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/latex/latex_emitter.runa" as LaTeXEmitter
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/latex/latex_to_hir.runa" as LaTeXHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR module readers (self-contained kind-tagged tree)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The LaTeX HIR module is a record whose type tag sits at offset 0 and whose
flattened items list (every node enrolled via add_to_module) sits at offset
16. This reader returns that items list so the probe can scan it exactly the
way a backend would when it walks the module top-level.
@End Reasoning
Process called "module_items" takes module_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If module_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_integer from Memory with module_ptr, 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the node-type tag (offset 0) for any HIR node, or 0 for a null
pointer. Mirrors how the production backend dispatches on the kind tag.
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_kind" takes node_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_integer from Memory with node_ptr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Locates the first node in a module's flat items list whose type tag equals
the requested kind. Linear scan matches the renderer's dispatch loop. Returns
0 when no node of that kind exists so callers can assert presence with
assert_not_null.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_node_by_kind" takes module_ptr as Integer, kind as Integer returns Integer:
    Let items be proc module_items with module_ptr
    If items is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc list_length from List with items
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let node be proc list_get from List with items, index
        Let this_kind be proc node_kind with node
        If this_kind is equal to kind:
            Return node
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counts how many nodes in the flat items list carry the requested type tag.
Used to assert the two-item list count without assuming the items are
contiguous in the flattened sequence.
@End Reasoning
Process called "count_nodes_by_kind" takes module_ptr as Integer, kind as Integer returns Integer:
    Let items be proc module_items with module_ptr
    If items is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc list_length from List with items
    Let index be 0
    Let total be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let node be proc list_get from List with items, index
        Let this_kind be proc node_kind with node
        If this_kind is equal to kind:
            Set total to total plus 1
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return total
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads a string-pointer field at the given byte offset of a HIR node. The
LaTeX frontend stores text payloads (class names, titles, formatted text,
environment names) as string pointers via memory_set_pointer, so the reader
pulls them back with the matching pointer accessor.
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_string_field" takes node_ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    If node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with node_ptr, offset
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "LaTeX translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative document: documentclass + usepackage in the preamble, then
    a section heading, a bold-text command, an itemize list with two items,
    and an inline-math span inside the document body.
    :End Note
    Let source be "\\documentclass{article}\n\\usepackage{amsmath}\n\\begin{document}\n\\section{Intro Title}\n\\textbf{bold text}\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\item first\n\\item second\n\\end{itemize}\n$a+b$\n\\end{document}\n"

    Note: --- Stage 1: source -> HIR ---
    Let hir1 be proc latex_to_hir from LaTeXEmitter with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "frontend produced HIR module", hir1

    Let root_kind be proc node_kind with hir1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR root is latex document", root_kind, HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENT from LaTeXHIR

    Let items be proc module_items with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module has items list", items

    Let item_total be proc list_length from List with items
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "module items list is non-empty", item_total, 0

    Note: --- Documentclass: class name ---
    Let docclass be proc find_node_by_kind with hir1, HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENTCLASS from LaTeXHIR
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module contains a documentclass node", docclass

    Let class_name be proc node_string_field with docclass, 8
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "documentclass class is 'article'", class_name, "article"

    Note: --- Usepackage: package name ---
    Let usepackage be proc find_node_by_kind with hir1, HIR_LATEX_USEPACKAGE from LaTeXHIR
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module contains a usepackage node", usepackage

    Let package_name be proc node_string_field with usepackage, 8
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "usepackage package is 'amsmath'", package_name, "amsmath"

    Note: --- Section: title ---
    Let section be proc find_node_by_kind with hir1, HIR_LATEX_SECTION from LaTeXHIR
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module contains a section node", section

    Let section_title be proc node_string_field with section, 8
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "section title is 'Intro Title'", section_title, "Intro Title"

    Note: --- Bold text formatting ---
    Let bold be proc find_node_by_kind with hir1, HIR_LATEX_TEXT_BOLD from LaTeXHIR
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module contains a bold-text node", bold

    Let bold_text be proc node_string_field with bold, 8
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "bold text is 'bold text'", bold_text, "bold text"

    Note: --- Itemize environment + two items ---
    Let itemize be proc find_node_by_kind with hir1, HIR_LATEX_ITEMIZE from LaTeXHIR
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module contains an itemize environment", itemize

    Let env_name be proc node_string_field with itemize, 8
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "itemize environment name is 'itemize'", env_name, "itemize"

    Note:
    Each \item is lowered to a HIR_LIST_LITERAL node (the kind tag used by
    translate_list_item) and flattened into the module items list. There are
    exactly two items in the source. translate_argument_content also emits
    HIR_LIST_LITERAL blocks for braced arguments, so the count is asserted as
    "at least 2" to keep the structural check robust to argument lowering.
    :End Note
    Let list_item_count be proc count_nodes_by_kind with hir1, HIR_LIST_LITERAL from HIR
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "module has 2 or more list-item blocks", list_item_count, 1

    Note: --- Inline math ---
    Let math_inline be proc find_node_by_kind with hir1, HIR_LATEX_MATH_INLINE from LaTeXHIR
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module contains an inline-math node", math_inline

    Note: --- Stage 2: HIR -> LaTeX text ---
    Let emitted be proc hir_to_latex from LaTeXEmitter with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced LaTeX text", emitted

    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted LaTeX is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with emitted, 0
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted LaTeX begins with backslash (92)", first_char, 92

    Note: --- Stage 3: re-parse emitted LaTeX -> HIR, assert stable structure ---
    Let hir2 be proc latex_to_hir from LaTeXEmitter with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted LaTeX produced HIR", hir2

    Let root2_kind be proc node_kind with hir2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed root is latex document", root2_kind, HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENT from LaTeXHIR

    Let docclass2 be proc find_node_by_kind with hir2, HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENTCLASS from LaTeXHIR
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed module keeps a documentclass", docclass2

    Let class_name2 be proc node_string_field with docclass2, 8
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed documentclass class is 'article'", class_name2, "article"

    Let section2 be proc find_node_by_kind with hir2, HIR_LATEX_SECTION from LaTeXHIR
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed module keeps a section", section2

    Let section_title2 be proc node_string_field with section2, 8
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed section title is 'Intro Title'", section_title2, "Intro Title"

    Let itemize2 be proc find_node_by_kind with hir2, HIR_LATEX_ITEMIZE from LaTeXHIR
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed module keeps an itemize environment", itemize2

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
